               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-416-person2155">
                  ANN 
                  GIBBONS
               <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2155" type="surname" value="GIBBONS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2155" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2155" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of John Gibbons - we live in <placeName id="t18260914-416-crimeloc2340">Type-court, St. Luke's</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-416-crimeloc2340" type="placeName" value="Type-court, St. Luke's"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-416-crimeloc2340" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-416-off2338 t18260914-416-crimeloc2340"></join>. On the 11th of July I left the house at five o'clock in the morning, and left William and Robert Gibbons, my two children, in bed and asleep; the house is let out in tenements; I have only the lower part. I went to Spitalfields-market - I left the room door on the latch; my husband had gone out some time before; I returned at six o'clock, and was told I had been robbed; I went to the watch-house, and saw my apron and a shirt, which I had seen safe at five o'clock - the shirt was on the bed, and I think the apron was over the head of the bed; the prisoner was a stranger.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-416-person2156">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  PEARES
               <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2156" type="surname" value="PEARES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2156" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-416-person2156" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Thomas Peares - we lodge in this house. On the morning of the 11th of July I was coming up from the cellar, and heard the room door shut; I said, "Is that Mrs. Gibbons," but no person answered; I went out at the street door, and saw the prisoner, who had a basket, with an apron or something in it I went and told her she did not belong to that place - she said she did; I brought her back, and said to her, "These things are not your's, for I saw the woman tying up onions in this apron, and this is the shirt the little sailor boy wore"- she then threw them down.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-416-person2157">
                  WILLIAM 
                  RICE
